<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Truck and van sector shows signs of upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE first cautious signs appeared last month that commercial vehicles as a
whole may be starting to follow the UK market for new cars out of recession.
Recovery is already well under way in the truck industry. Statistics from
the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders show that last month's sales
of trucks over 3.5 tonnes jumped by 19.8 per cent to 4,910, compared with
4,097 in the same period last year.
The August total lifted total truck sales for the first eight months of the
year to 22,392, an 8.53 per cent increase over last year's 20,633.
Sales of light vans and panel vans - such as the Ford Escort and Transit
respectively - continued below last year's severely depressed levels, but by
a smaller margin than earlier in the year.
Light van sales were 6.72 per cent lower in August than in the same month
last year, at 8,913 compared with 9,545, but this was an improvement on the
first eight months as a whole, during which sales were 8.01 per cent lower
than the equivalent period last year.
Similarly, sales of panel vans in August, at 14,536, were only 4.08 per cent
lower than a year ago, compared with the 5.55 per cent cut recorded for the
the first eight months.
The commercial vehicles statistics reinforce figures covering the market for
used cars, which also indicate that economic activity is picking up.
Overall, 31,085 commercial vehicles were sold in August - a drop of only
1.95 per cent on the 31,707 achieved in the same month last year. Total
sales for the first eight months of the year were 4.76 per cent below the
period last year, at 135,340 compared with 142,098.
The share taken by imports last month was sharply higher, at 44.87 per cent
compared with 40.81 per cent, and 40.78 per cent for the first eight months
compared with 35.86 per cent a year ago.
The small vans sector is seeing a sharply increased challenge from Renault,
whose sales jumped 72 per cent in August and by 35 per cent in the first
eight months of the year. The main market casualty has been Rover, with
sales of the ageing Maestro van falling by 36 per cent so far this year.
The share of panel van sales taken by LDV, the management buy-out led
manufacturer of Leyland Daf vans, fell sharply in August compared with a
year ago, from 10.8 per cent to 7.8 per cent. But with August by far the
biggest sales month for commercial vehicles - as with cars, because of the
new registration prefix - LDV maintains that the drop reflects the still
relatively low production after LDV emerged from receivership in May.
The Iveco Ford group has been able to strengthen its hold on the truck
sector, with its share rising to 25.9 per cent in August compared with 17.98
per cent for the once market-leading Leyland Daf.
