<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Consumer goods lift index
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICE RISES for a range of goods including clothes, shoes, furniture, eggs
and tobacco were behind a larger-than-expected increase in the retail prices
index last month.
In the 12 months to August the RPI rose 1.7 per cent from 1.4 per cent in
the year to July. The year-on-year figure for last month was the highest
since March.
Between July and August the index rose 0.4 per cent from 140.7 to 141.3.
Of the 14 types of goods and services monitored by the Central Statistical
Office in calculating the index, 10 showed a higher year-on-year increase in
prices in August compared with July.
Between July and last month, prices of clothes and footwear rose 1.5 per
cent, the biggest August increase for 16 years. That took the year-on-year
change for this element of the RPI to 2 per cent, from 0.4 per cent in July.
Household goods including furniture and cookers saw price rises of 1.2 per
cent in the month to August, the largest increase for this time of the year
since 1979.
Pressure on the index also came from a 0.2 per cent increase in food prices
between July and August.
Petrol prices fell slightly during August, though by less than in the same
month last year. This was reflected in overall motoring costs showing a 5.3
per cent increase last month from a year previously, compared with 4.9 per
cent in the year to July.
</TEXT>
