<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Taurus successor riles fund managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Institutional Fund Managers' Association has complained that a committee
set up to consider a successor to the failed Taurus settlements system
mainly consists of those with a potential commercial interest in the
project.
The trade body for UK fund managers has told the Bank of England that the
Crest committee - established by the Bank - contains only one institutional
investor, representing the largest group which will ultimately use the
system.
Most of the other members are representatives of custodial banks or
registrar banks - whom the Bank had said would play a secondary role in
deciding the specifications for the new system.
After the collapse of Taurus - which aimed to introduce paperless trading in
the City of London and narrow the settlement period to three days from two
weeks - City commentators said the Stock Exchange had tried too hard to
satisfy the demands of the different service providers such as custodians
and registrars, and the project became far too complex and expensive. The
Bank of England said it would establish Crest as a successor system and the
needs of end-users, such as institutions, would be paramount.
In August IFMA wrote to Mr Pen Kent, associate director at the Bank, to
express concern about the committee's structure. In reply Mr Kent offered to
let the group meet Mr Iain Saville, the Bank's project controller for Crest.
One IFMA member said: 'We are concerned about the lack of consultations
about business specifications.' In particular, the fund managers are
concerned about the recommendation that each Crest participant be allocated
a single account. Another IFMA member said: 'That means that our clients who
want their securities designated in their own names cannot have that.' About
85 per cent of UK pension funds insist that securities be held in their own
name, not in the name of the fund manager's nominee company.
Also, the institutions, which own 80 per cent of the shares traded in
London, are concerned about being held hostage to price increases if a
commercial vendor won a franchise to exclusively provide a portion of the
settlement service.
A fund manager said: 'They say they are concerned about the needs of end
users. But what they really want is a convenient system devised by the
service providers and we will have to fit into that.'
Among the members are Mr Brian Finnegan, head of settlement operations at
the London Stock Exchange - which, Mr Kent has suggested, may have little
role to play in securities settlement after Crest. Also on the panel is Mr
Ralph Walrond, chief registrar at Lloyds Bank Registrars.
Other members include Mr Terry Pearson, senior securities adviser at Royal
Bank of Scotland Securities Services, the largest independent custodian for
UK pension funds, Mr Alistair Reid, director of custody at Barclays Bank and
Mr Geoff Newman, vice president at Chase Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<XX>
