<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Retail sales edge upwards in 'fragile' climate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHOP SALES are steadily edging upwards, even though the sector's commercial
performance last month was patchy, according to government figures released
yesterday.
In the three months to the end of August, seasonally-adjusted retail volumes
increased 1 per cent compared with the previous three months and by 3.8 per
cent on the corresponding period last year.
However, sales volumes in August were up just 0.1 per cent on the month
before, when volumes fell 0.3 per cent on June. Shops selling clothes and
shoes, and those selling a mixture of food and non-edible items, performed
particularly weakly in August, according to the Central Statistical Office's
figures.
The data underlines how retail sales, which account for about a quarter of
gross domestic product, are continuing their pattern of slow upward movement
in line with signs of economic recovery.
In the three months to the end of May, volumes increased 0.9 per cent
compared with the previous three months, while between December last year
and February the three-monthly increase was 0.6 per cent.
Between July and August, food shops saw a 0.4 per cent increase in their
sales, while 'mixed retail' stores suffered a downturn of 0.3 per cent.
The British Retail Consortium, a trade body for the sector, said many shops
were experiencing 'difficult trading conditions', in spite of signs of an
end to recession. People remained reluctant to buy non-essential items, a
sign that consumer confidence was 'fragile'.
In the area of clothing and footwear, where sales volumes slipped 1.1 per
cent between July and August, the consortium said: 'Basic necessity clothing
did comparatively well while the more exotic, less 'necessary' designer end
fared badly.'
Sales last month of recorded music, videos, furniture and carpets were poor,
while stores selling DIY goods experienced only modest growth.
A bright spot was that the large numbers of tourists in August pushed up
sales in many big London stores, a trend helped by the continuing weakness
of the pound.
</TEXT>
