<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Dangers of a US share and bond bubble: Group warns of
'irresponsible' Fed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US Federal Reserve monetary policy is irresponsibly expansionary and
creating a bubble in bond and share prices, according to a group of US
monetarists.
If it does not change course soon, the US will face an 'asset price bubble'
similar to that which destabilised financial markets in Japan in the late
1980s, the group says.
In recent days the bull market has shown signs of fragility with sharp falls
in share and bond prices. In late trading yesterday, however, confidence
returned, pushing the yield on the long bond back below 6 per cent. The Dow
Jones industrial average closed 17.89 higher at 3,633.65.
The critique comes from the shadow open market committee, a group of
economists set up 20 years ago to challenge conventional wisdom on US
monetary policy. The monetary base has risen 11 per cent in the past year -
double the rate of growth of nominal GDP of 5 to 5.5 per cent, Prof Allan
Meltzer of Carnegie Mellon University, the head of the group, said this
week, publishing its twice-yearly report. The economy is thus awash with
liquidity most of which has found its way into financial markets.
Long bond yields have fallen steeply, he claims, not because of confidence
that inflation will remain low but because, with growth of reserves far
exceeding loan demand, excess cash is being used to purchase government
securities.
'We believe the Fed has delayed too long in responding to an emerging bubble
in asset prices,' he says. 'The time has long passed when the Fed should
have tightened monetary policy.'
The criticism that Fed policy is too lax runs counter to the views of many
mainstream economists who argue that the Fed ought to consider cutting rates
further in order to stimulate a still sluggish economic recovery. Those
wanting the Fed to be more expansionary complain that M2, the main measure
of broad money, has barely grown at all in recent years.
Prof Meltzer and colleagues, however, prefer to focus on narrow measures of
the money supply, such as the monetary base which consists of currency in
circulation plus banks' reserves with the Fed. Unlike M2 this measure has
not been distorted by a shift from bank deposits to money market instruments
in recent years.
The initial impact of excessive growth of the monetary base is to raise
asset prices. But it will eventually feed through into higher consumer price
inflation, the group warns. The Fed has thus been lulled into a false sense
of security.
'We urge the Fed to slow the growth of the monetary base by three percentage
points to an annual rate of no more than 8 per cent,' says Prof Meltzer.
He refuses to predict how large an increase in short-term rates this might
require but concedes that it will be more than the quarter-point increase
which was recommended by some analysts earlier in the summer.
In congressional hearings, Mr Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has
indicated that real short-term interest rates (the nominal interest rate
minus inflation) are close to zero and cannot be maintained at this
historically low level indefinitely.
But the Fed has so far postponed a raising of rates because economic growth
has been slower than expected and because an apparent spurt in inflation in
the spring has since been reversed.
</TEXT>
