<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Task force for telecom future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US administration yesterday set up a task force to co-ordinate
government and private sector efforts to develop new 'electronic highways'
for voice and data communications.
Vice-President Al Gore said the task force would review existing federal
laws and rules governing the telecommunications market - many of them dating
back to the 1930s - and seek to speed the creation of a national information
infrastructure.
The plan Mr Gore announced yesterday outlines a future of telecommuting,
long-distance education, interactive television and widespread access to
databases through a network of cable and satellite links.
'It's critically important to the economic future of the United States,' Mr
Gore said.
The task force is expected to conduct a thorough review of the
Communications Act of 1934, which has been modified over the years but casts
a dominating shadow over the entire telecommunications field.
Designed in the days of a monopoly telephone company, the act is based on a
principle of universal access which has been somewhat overtaken by
technological developments.
Mr George Fisher, the chief executive of Motorola and chairman of the
Council on Competitiveness, a business grouping, yesterday welcomed the
administration's policy announcement.
'We are especially pleased to see the establishment of an information
infrastructure task force and a private-sector advisory committee, both
vital to success,' Mr Fisher said.
At stake in the discussion on a national information infrastructure are huge
economic interests.
While almost all of the US is equipped with basic telephones and
televisions, the development of satellite broadcasting, cable television and
computer bulletin boards and databases has left a higgledy-piggledy web of
often incompatible technologies.
While visionaries dream of fibre optic cables taking such services to every
home, cynics suggest this sort of cabling would cost Dollars 200bn to
Dollars 400bn (Pounds 130bn to Pounds 260bn).
Compressing digital information on to existing telephone lines, on the other
hand, could be much cheaper but would offer far more limited capacity, a
maximum of perhaps 144,000 bits per second, compared with several billion
bps for fibre optics.
</TEXT>
