<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Germans argue social case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The German government submission to the European Commission's review of jobs
and competitiveness argues in support of a strong social dimension,
welcoming a greater role for the social partners - unions and employers -
written into the Maastricht Treaty, writes David Goodhart.
In addition to existing directives it suggests seven general rights which
workers throughout the EC should enjoy: equal treatment for people in
part-time employment; ban on discrimination against workers who exercise
their legal rights; the right of the worker to be heard in internal company
matters; protection of privacy; entitlement to four weeks leave; adequate
protection against dismissal and ban on sex discrimination.
