<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Rise in inflation hits markets: FT-SE 100 falls 38.6 points
 -Government strategy under pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LARGER than expected increase in inflation increased the pressure
yesterday on the government's economic strategy and sparked big falls in
London bond and share prices.
The FT-SE 100 index of leading equities suffered its biggest setback for
seven months and the gilt-edged securities market had its worst day since
the UK left the European exchange rate mechanism a year ago today.
News that the retail prices index rose in the year to August by 1.7 per
cent, up from 1.4 per cent in the 12 months to July, came the day after
government ministers imposed a near-freeze on public-sector pay next year on
the grounds that inflationary pressures were weak.
It provoked an angry response from the Labour party and union leaders
representing some of the 5m workers affected. The change between July and
August in the year-on-year RPI rate was the highest monthly increase since
November 1991. It was triggered by a broadly based rise in prices of retail
goods and services, particularly affecting clothes, shoes and household
goods.
The Treasury's favoured measure of underlying inflation - the year-on-year
increase in the RPI excluding mortgage interest payments - edged up to 3.1
per cent in August from 2.9 per cent in July to its highest level since
March.
The figures affected perceptions among UK investors about the outlook for
inflation, the weakness of which has helped prolong the recent London share
and bond rally. With long-dated gilts closing down 2 points, investors also
sold London equities, pushing the FT-SE 100 down 38.6 to 2,989.4, its
biggest one-day fall for seven months.
Investor nervousness about the UK economic outlook was heightened by
separate Central Statistical Office figures indicating barely visible growth
in retail sales volumes in August, and by weaknesses in share and bond
prices across the rest of Europe prompted by worries about the effects of
high interest rates and poor corporate earnings.
Sterling lost ground against the D-Mark, closing in London at DM2.4725, down
more than 1 pfennig, with little change in New York. Against a weak dollar,
the pound strengthened by half a cent to Dollars 1.5515, easing in New York
to Dollars 1.549.
The news increased speculation that Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, may
have difficulties keeping the underlying measure of inflation within the
bottom half of the Treasury's 1-4 per cent target range within the life of
this parliament.
However, the Treasury stressed that inflation remained low by postwar
standards and the figures met with a calm response from Mr John Major.
Speaking in the Midlands, the prime minister said: 'People want steady
growth with low inflation. That's what we're planning for in the long-term.'
Mr Gordon Brown, the Labour shadow chancellor, ridiculed government claims
that it had created an 'inflation-free' environment and said price pressures
would increase in the next few months. Mr Bill Morris, Transport and General
Workers' Union general secretary, said government ministers were 'living in
an economic fantasy world'.
