<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Retail sales data fail to
provide lift for Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
DISAPPOINTING news on inflation and a weakening bond market pushed share
prices on Wall Street lower, as stronger than expected retail sales figures
failed to impress equity investors, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 18.45 down at 3,615.76. The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 lost 2.16 to 459.90, while the American SE composite shed 1.54
to 452.76 and the Nasdaq composite fell 7.68 to 732.64. New York SE trading
volume came to 258.6m shares.
Stocks opened moderately lower in reaction to an early sell-off in the
Treasury bond market. The bearish mood was triggered by the release of
August's consumer price index, which showed a 0.3 per cent rise in retail
prices last month. Analysts had expected a 0.1 per cent uptick. A surprising
0.6 per cent decline in the August producer price index, released last
Friday, had served to heighten expectations of moderating inflation on the
retail level as well.
As the day progressed and the bond market tumbled, stock prices slipped
further. Investors took little comfort in a 0.2 per cent increase in August
retail sales, even though a slight fall had been predicted. Any indication
of growing consumption - and a more buoyant economy - was undercut by an
upward revision in July's figure, to a 0.3 per cent increase, which suggests
a declining month-to-month trend.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, edged Dollars  3/8 down to Dollars 64 3/8
after it announced 5,000 job cuts by the end of 1994. Other leading US
airlines, which on Monday cut fares by up to 45 per cent, lost ground as
well. UAL, operator of United Air Lines, shed Dollars 4 1/4 to Dollars 142
1/4 and Delta Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 52 5/8 .
Viacom, which this week agreed to acquire Paramount Communications in a
cash-and-stock transaction now valued at Dollars 7.9bn, dropped on a report
that heavy buying by Viacom's chairman had helped to boost its share price
in the weeks before the announcement. On the Amex, Viacom's class A shares
fell Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 61 1/2 , while its B non-voting stock was down
Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 55 3/8 . Paramount slipped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars
63 1/8 .
After a big sell-off late on Monday, Compaq Computer sought to downplay its
announcement of relatively flat personal computer shipments in the second
half. By the close the shares had recovered Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 56 1/2 .
Home Depot dropped Dollars 4 to Dollars 36 1/4 after Goldman Sachs removed
the building supply retailer from its recommended list.
Canada
TORONTO closed mixed after busy trading. The TSE 300 index gained just 0.3
at 3,972.1, but declining issues outnumbered advances by 445 to 313. Volume
was 68.5m shares.
Eight of the 14 sub-indices were lower, led by energy, off 1.0 per cent. The
gold shares index, after dropping 5.4 per cent on Monday, rallied 2.7 per
cent, helped by a recovery in the bullion price, which firmed USDollars 2 an
ounce to USDollars 345 in New York.
