<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Figures fail to hold D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEALERS called a halt to Monday's profit-taking against the D-Mark
yesterday, pushing the German currency back up against the dollar and most
European currencies, writes James Blitz.
Few had interpreted Monday's sharp fall in the value of the D-Mark as
anything more than position squaring after a sustained rise. Yesterday, the
German currency's power was reasserted. It gained  1/2 pfennig against the
dollar to close at DM1.6065. In New York the dollar ended at DM1.6097.
The D-Mark's rise came in spite of US data which might have suggested that
the Federal Reserve was leaning towards a tightening of policy.
In particular, US consumer price inflation rose 0.3 per cent in August,
against expectations of a 0.1 per cent increase.
The story of D-Mark strength dominated an otherwise untidy European session.
The German currency was stronger against the French franc, ending at
FFr3.487 from a previous FFr3.482. This was in spite of reduced optimism in
French money markets about lower rates.
Sterling closed unchanged at DM2.4850. Money market dealers increasingly
assume that there will be no cut in sterling base rates before the end of
this year. But the pound may have been hindered yesterday by slightly
disappointing manufacturing output figures.
The yen was higher at the start of trading amid signs that Japanese life
insurance companies were selling huge quantities of Australian dollars for
Japan's currency.
The selling pushed the Australian currency down to a new all-time low
against its trade weighted index. But the yen's strength did not last long.
The currency slipped back against the dollar in Europe as dealers braced
themselves for tomorrow's announcement of a fiscal stimulus package by the
Japanese authorities.
The US dollar closed at Y105.80 from a previous Y106.25. It finished New
York trading at Y105.85.
Mr Steve Hannah, chief economist at IBJ International in London, said
currency dealers would be looking for a number of key pointers in the
Japanese package. The first was the size of the stimulus. In his view, the
market is anticipating a fiscal boost of some 5 trillion yen, with plenty of
scope for tax cuts.
An announcement of a cut of  1/2 percentage point in the official discount
rate is also anticipated, although Mr Hannah thinks this might not take
immediate effect. A third key issue will be whether the Japanese authorities
set a concrete target for the reduction in the trade surplus. Japanese
officials have contradicted each other when asked if this is being
considered.
Tomorrow's announcements will be a milestone in the medium term outlook for
the yen. The recent sharp downturn in the yen has been predicated on the
belief that Japan will offer something concrete to President Clinton in
Washington next week.
</TEXT>
