<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Delta shares fallas group douses recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Delta fell 8 per cent after the UK cables and engineering group
became the latest industrial company to disappoint the market's hopes of
recovery.
The group said: 'The UK recovery as far as manufacturing is concerned
remains more anaemic than many observers suggest, and activity in
continental Europe has yet to see the benefit of progressive interest rate
reductions.'
Delta has cut its workforce by a third since 1989 and had been identified as
one of the companies best placed to benefit from any upturn. The shares were
marked up sharply in the spring, but yesterday fell 43p to 511p after the
group announced a small drop in profits.
Mr Geoffrey Wilson, chairman, said that in April he had seen renewed signs
of a slow, if patchy, recovery except in continental Europe: 'This pattern
has persisted with continental European markets remaining depressed and any
recovery in the UK and Australia being limited to specific sectors of the
economy.'
Pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 30.97m to Pounds 29.11m in the six months
to July 3, in spite of a 6 per cent increase in sales, from Pounds 402m to
Pounds 428m.
Mr Wilson said exports from the UK rose by 14 per cent from the already high
levels reached last year to a new record of Pounds 83.8m, greatly helping to
offset low domestic demand. Currency translation added Pounds 1.25m to the
profits figure.
Cables continued to suffer from volatile markets and severe price
competition, with operating profits down from Pounds 5.6m to to Pounds 5.4m.
However, restructuring improved the performance at Surprenant, Delta's US
cable subsidiary, which suffered from defence cuts.
Lower demand across continental Europe reduced the profitability of the
engineering division from Pounds 11.2m to Pounds 10.4m, but industrial
services increased profits to Pounds 9.1m (from Pounds 8.4m), as did circuit
protection, to Pounds 8.1m from Pounds 7.4m.
Group gearing rose slightly, from 26 to 28 per cent. Interest payments rose
from Pounds 1.6m to Pounds 3.9m.
Mr Robert Easton, chief executive, said Delta was continuing to invest in
new products and was interested in further acquisitions, particularly in the
US.
Earnings per share dipped to 12.5p (from 12.7p), but the interim dividend
was held at 4.2p.
