<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / NatWest picks CIN chief to run investment arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Paul Whitney is quitting as chief executive of CIN Management, manager of
British Coal's pension funds, to join National Westminster Bank as a
managing director in charge of investment management.
The appointment will be followed by a radical reorganisation of NatWest's
fund management operations. Mr Martin Owen, chief executive of NatWest
Markets, said the group's diverse investment management businesses would be
brought together into one centralised operation under Mr Whitney.
County NatWest Investment Management, the bank's main investment arm - which
will be renamed NatWest Investment Management - has suffered departures of
senior executives in recent years, undermining its ability to attract UK
pension funds according to pension consultants.
Mr Whitney was first approached by NatWest two months ago. He said yesterday
he decided to join the bank because the new job is potentially far bigger
than his current one. CIN manages Pounds 15bn of funds. 'NatWest has up to
Pounds 30bn,' he said.
However, at the moment this is divided between five different parts of the
bank.
Mr Owen said NatWest took the decision several months ago to bring its fund
management operations together. The bank then decided to search for an
executive to manage the process.
In the past two years, NatWest has adopted a similar strategy with its other
commercial and investment banking operations and has put all of them into
NatWest Markets under Mr Owen.
According to data from pension consultants William M. Mercer and Co, CNWIM's
average UK pension fund portfolio underperformed the market median from 1987
until the middle of 1992.
Increasingly, CNWIM has marketed itself as a 'quantitative' fund manager
incorporating both passive index-tracking techniques and 'active'
mathematical stock and asset selection processes.
Mr Whitney has been at CIN for 10 years. The investment decision of which he
is proudest was the sale for Pounds 800m of the group's US property
portfolio during 1988 and 1989, before prices collapsed.
</TEXT>
