<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Factory output growth weaker than expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S manufacturing output bounced back in July after falling sharply in
June, but changes to the way the figures are collated show that growth so
far this year is not as strong as previously reported.
Output in July showed a 0.7 per cent rise over June, when there was a 2.1
per cent fall from the previous month. Compared with the same month a year
ago, July output was up 1.7 per cent.
Although manufacturing output is still growing faster than other sectors of
the economy, a new series of Central Statistical Office figures shows growth
in the first half of the year as much weaker than thought.
Figures rebased to 1990 show that output grew by 1.2 per cent and 0.6 per
cent in the first and second quarters of this year, against 2 per cent and
1.4 per cent under the old series. However a drop in production towards the
end of last year was not as steep as previously recorded and, compared with
a year ago, the growth rates for the first six months of the year were
revised downwards only slightly.
The latest figures show that in the three months to July, manufacturing
output grew by 0.1 per cent compared with the previous three-month period.
However, compared with the same three months a year ago, output was up 2.2
per cent.
The CSO said the changes would not have a big impact on gross domestic
product. They may change the quarterly profile of non-oil GDP, but the
strength of manufacturing output on a year-on-year basis means the changes
are unlikely to alter the recent trend of steady growth.
The monthly rise in manufacturing output was concentrated in investment
goods. Output of this category rose by 1.5 per cent compared with June, when
it dropped 2.9 per cent.
The strongest industries were textiles, leather and clothing, coke, petrol
and nuclear fuels. Food, drink and tobacco and chemicals suffered the
sharpest quarter-on-quarter drops.
Mining and quarrying, which under the new series no longer counts as
manufacturing, grew by 6.3 per cent compared with the previous three months.
Within this, coal production was 14.7 per cent lower, reflecting
lower-volume contracts between British Coal and the electricity generating
companies from April.
Electricity, gas and water production was also strong, rising 4.1 per cent
in the latest three months.
Shape of recovery, Page 12
Currencies, Page 37
London stocks, Page 46
See Lex
</TEXT>
