<DOCNO>FT933-3189</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DIOCVADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930915
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Are we ready for 'the dark heart of the glory that was Rome'? It is offered
by BBC2's history series Timewatch which returns with an account of
activities in the Colosseum at the time of Julius Caesar. It seems these
included tightrope walking elephants, Christians used as human torches, and
women fighting gladiator dwarfs (8.00).
The Radio 4 series In Business reports on 'Europe Unchained'. It is a year
since the pound left the ERM, and in July the mechanism virtually broke
down. The question is: 'Can the rest of Europe imitate Britain and turn
monetary disaster into economic recovery?' Is that what we are experiencing?
Switch to Radio 3 and you will catch almost the whole of its programme on
the semi-finals in the Leeds International Piano Competition.
Inside Story (9.30 BBC1) tells how Battersea Park School, is being turned
into Battersea Technical College with Pounds 2.5m worth of science and
computer labs and a 'technology aptitude test'. Some condemn this but
parents respect a school where you have to pass a test to get in and already
applications outnumber places.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
