<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Performance pay plan for teachers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERFORMANCE-related pay is to be introduced for teachers under plans
announced by the government yesterday.
Fourteen schools are to test ways of relating pay to performance - judged,
for example, by appraisal interviews. The tests will be monitored by the
School Teachers' Review Body, the independent group which advises on pay,
and by the Department for Education.
The department said there were few teaching posts left unfilled and
recruitment to training courses was healthy. It said: 'The aim must now be
to ensure pay is used in the most effective way to raise standards. Schools
should now respond by identifying good performance in their teachers and
rewarding it.'
The National Union of Teachers is boycotting appraisal interviews where they
could be used for performance-related pay. The Professional Association of
Teachers said: 'We had been willing to consider performance-related pay in
principle, but see no evidence that its adoption in schools would benefit
either the profession or students.'
The 14 pioneer schools are: Ashton-on-Mersey School and Audenshaw High
School in Manchester; Blatchington Mills School, E Sussex; Campsmount
School, S Yorks; the Cecil Jones High School, Essex; The Chase High School,
Hereford &amp; Worcester; Crofton School, Stubbington, Hampshire; Deers Wood
School, Avon; Eight Ash Green C of E Primary School, Essex; Furze Platt
School, Berks; Hazelwich School, W Sussex; Lamphey County Primary School,
Dyfed; St Martin's School, Essex; and Westlands School, Kent.
</TEXT>
