<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / A-levels 'past sell-by date' says headmasters' leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE A-LEVEL examination is 'past its sell-by date', the chairman of the
Headmasters' Conference, which represents the UK's leading independent boys'
schools, said yesterday.
Mr Robin Wilson, headmaster of Trinity School, Croydon, told the
conference's annual meeting in Oxford that the surge in post-16 education,
the expansion of national education targets and the pressures on higher
education 'all suggest that we are in the dying years of our present
system'.
His comments add to several recent calls to reform A-levels so that
sixth-formers can study a broader range of subjects. Sir Ron Dearing,
chairman of the Schools Curriculum and Assessment Authority, is preparing a
report into 'the merits of a modified approach to the curriculum from 14 to
16, which retains a mandatory core but which provides a smoother transition
to study post-16 education, through a wide range of options'.
Mr Wilson gave strong support to those calling for the age of 14 to replace
16 as an educational watershed. He said: 'The national curriculum has been
designed for a system which is programmed until the age of 16. Evidence is
growing that such a timescale is out of date and unhelpful.'
He said that the framework of discussion was now the 14-19 age group, and
that A-levels demanded a commitment to a limited number 'and too often a
limited range' of subjects at an early age.
Mr Wilson described the divide between vocational and academic education as
'artificial', and said that it made pupils choose decisively at an
undeveloped age.
A-levels were also attacked yesterday by Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education
secretary, who described them as 'too restrictive, too narrow, and against
the interests of the pupils who take them'. She said that neither higher
education nor employers supported the A-level system.
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, yesterday appointed the members of
the Schools Curriculum and Assessment Authority who will work under Sir Ron
and will have control of the national curriculum and its tests. Half are
teachers.
They include Mr Graham Mackenzie, group chief executive of UES Holdings, Mr
David Quarmby, joint managing director of J Sainsbury, and Mrs Shahwar
Sadeque, director of computer software company Art of Intelligence and a
governor of the BBC.
</TEXT>
