<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Barclays to sack 500 in staff cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARCLAYS BANK said yesterday that 500 staff in London and the south-east
were likely to lose their jobs in the first compulsory redundancies it has
ever made in its branch network.
It said that as many as 800 staff in the region were 'surplus' to its needs
and that much of the reduction it wanted could not be met through its
voluntary redundancy programme.
Mr John Cotton, Barclay's personnel director, said: 'This is something we
all sought to avoid but it is justified by the needs of the business and we
have to face up to it. We feel great regret but these jobs are lost
forever.'
He said there were no further plans for compulsory job losses in the region
or elsewhere for the rest of this year, but that he could not rule out more
redundancies next year.
Mr Cotton left open the possibility that not all of the losses would have to
be compulsory, saying he was open to suggestions about how else to reduce
staffing. Discussions on the reductions will take place in the next few
months.
He said Barclays believed 500 of the 800 redundancies would be compulsory,
with some of the remainder met by voluntary departures and other 'surplus'
staff retained in case of further economic recovery.
Barclays said most of the reductions were not related to the recession but
reflected longer-term restructuring which required fewer staff.
They were part of a plan to reduce staff by 18,000 over five years from the
start of 1991, with London and the south-east most affected.
Bifu, the Banking Insurance and Finance Union, condemned the losses
yesterday and said the announcement had 'come out of the blue'.
It said its Barclays representatives had been told by senior bank officials
last week that the voluntary redundancy programme had been working well and
volunteers were even being refused.
'We are totally opposed to compulsory redundancies on principle,' Bifu said.
'They are unnecessary. This announcement shows that nobody in Barclays is
safe in 1994.'
It said it was likely to launch a publicity campaign andadded that it had
not ruled out the possibility of industrial action.
Barclays has reduced the number of staff by 13,500 to 45,000 since the start
of 1991, of which 9,000 have been in the branch network and the rest in
headquarters and support functions.
About 4,000 have lost their jobs in London and south-east branches.
It has cut branches from 2,400 to 2,200 in the same period and plans a
reduction to 1,900 over the next two years.
</TEXT>
