<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Usdaw voting boost for Smith
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH yesterday won a potentially significant victory in his battle
to introduce one-member-one-vote in the selection of Labour parliamentary
candidates. The Labour leader's campaign is opposed by some of the biggest
unions affiliated to the party.
The executive of Usdaw, the shopworkers' union which is the sixth-largest
affiliate to the party, decided that the union's delegation to the party
conference at the end of the month should be free to back Mr Smith's reform
proposals.
Mr Garfield Davies, Usdaw general secretary and a keen supporter of Mr
Smith, said that as the vote at the union's conference had not considered Mr
Smith's latest formula, the delegation should be free to back the leader.
The formula gives trade unionists who pay the political levy a cheap way to
become full party members.
The move will cause some ill-feeling in the union because its conference
voted against an earlier version of the Smith formula. But Mr Davies is
expected to get his own way.
Attention will now focus on whether leaders of Nupe, the public services
union, can make a similar shift.
Even if both Usdaw and Nupe do shift their votes, Mr Smith is not assured of
success. He will have to rely on either greater than expected support for
his reforms from constituency parties, or a stalemate in which no position
wins, allowing him to impose his wishes on the party.
</TEXT>
