<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Clarke warns on EC monetary rush
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE, the chancellor, yesterday warned European Community
countries against rushing to recreate the European monetary system as it
existed before the August currency crisis.
The chancellor called on the community to adopt economic and monetary
disciplines that were 'realistic and take account of the lessons from the
recent past'.
Delivering the Swiss Bank Corporation annual lecture in London, he said that
the EC's future economic discussions should be guided by three basic
principles:
Free markets and free trade, including the need to complete the single
market and the Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks.
Sound budgetary policies to keep real interest rates down to levels that
would make investment attractive.
Price stability, with monetary policies in each member state geared to
ensuring that the EC is a zone of low inflation.
These principles - clearly based on UK policy since the exit of sterling
from the European exchange rate mechanism a year ago - were, he said, the
right way to achieve greater convergence of economic policies while making
the community competitive with the outside world. 'Only when we have
achieved these objectives and only in the light of real experience, should
anyone think of going back to the question of monetary and exchange rate
policies,' the chancellor said.
Mr Clarke, who comes from the pro-European wing of the Conservative party,
was careful to provide some comfort for all sections of Tory opinion.
His opening words, which referred to European union instead of the EC, were
unlikely to endear him to Euro-sceptics. 'Britain,' he declared, 'will be a
member of the European union for the foreseeable future.'
But he depicted the Maastricht treaty as having broken the 'federal mould'
for the EC. The parts of the treaty that mattered 'are not the bureaucratic
and artificial timetable towards Emu' (economic and monetary union), but
subsidiarity, with its emphasis on limiting community action, and the
establishment of intergovernmental co-operation in foreign and security
policy and justice and home affairs.
These elements involved the EC 'in a totally different way'. Initiative
rested with the EC member states, rather than the commission. Voting, except
in very limited circumstances, was by unanimity. These elements were also
not subject to the jurisdiction of the European Court.
</TEXT>
