<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Delay to Cadbury measures agreed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING companies agreed with accounting standards setters yesterday on
delaying the implementation of parts of the Cadbury code of corporate
governance.
Directors have been concerned about the level of disclosure which they will
have to make under the code and said that they had been given insufficient
time to respond to the guidelines.
Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of the Financial Reporting Council, who called
yesterday's meeting, was last night still trying to seek approval for a new
timetable from Sir Adrian Cadbury, who chaired the committee on the
financial aspects of corporate governance.
Details of the agreement, which are expected to be issued in a statement by
the council today, will suggest a new framework for companies when they
report compliance with the most important aspects of the Cadbury code. These
include provision of interim financial statements, commentaries on the state
of internal controls, and on whether a company is a going concern or
financially viable.
Guidelines for companies on how to comment on such corporate governance
issues in their annual reports are likely to be delayed until next year.
Those at yesterday's meeting included representatives from the 100 Group of
finance directors of leading quoted companies, the Accounting Standards
Board, the Auditing Practices Board and the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales.
Sir Ron said yesterday that there would be regular co-ordination meetings
between companies and standards setters. There would be agreement on
timetables for the release of consultation documents, and on consultation
and implementation per-iods.
Quoted companies have been required by the Stock Exchange to provide a
statement of compliance with the code in their annual reports for financial
periods ending after June this year.
Yesterday's meeting solidified proposals initially discussed in July after
companies raised concerns that Cadbury and reporting requirements from other
organisations were over-burdening them with excessive demands.
The most public statements came from Mr Michael Lawrence, finance director
of life insurance group The Prudential and chairman of the 100. His views
reflected the discontent of a number of executives.
Disagreements on the drafting of the Cadbury guidelines have caused delays
to their launch, with the proposed statement on internal controls redrafted
at least 17 times.
</TEXT>
