FT  15 SEP 93 / World Trade News: Presidents combine to push Nafta cause
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE White House yesterday produced an extraordinary display of
bipartisanship, pageantry and salesmanship which laid to rest any doubts
about President Bill Clinton's commitment to congressional passage of a
North American Free Trade Agreement.
'We will make our case as hard and as well as we can,' he told supporters of
the pact between the US, Canada and Mexico. 'Nafta will create jobs - good
paying jobs. If I didn't believe that, I wouldn't support this agreement.'
The ceremony was for the signing of labour, environmental and import surge
side agreements. Presidents Clinton, Bush, Carter and Ford all urged support
for the deal.
In Mexico City, however, President Carlos Salinas yesterday played down the
importance of Nafta, in apparent response to concerns that the treaty might
be rejected by the US Congress. He said neither the treaty nor the side
accords were a panacea.
