<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 93 / Ceasefire agreed by Croat and Bosnian leaders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOSNIAN and Croatian leaders yesterday took a small step towards the
resumption of Bosnian peace talks by agreeing to an immediate halt to
fighting between mainly Moslem government troops and Croat forces in central
and south-west Bosnia.
The Croatian president, Mr Franjo Tudjman, said after talks in Geneva with
Mr Alija Izetbegovic, the Bosnian leader, that they had signed a ceasefire
accord, apparently to come into effect by noon on Saturday.
Most ceasefires to date have been ignored by the commanders on the ground.
But Mr Tudjman claimed the Bosnian Croat leader, Mr Mate Boban, who was not
in Geneva yesterday, would respect the agreement, which also calls for the
closure of all detention camps and free passage for humanitarian convoys.
However, the leaders made no announcement about when the peace talks might
reconvene, although they said that working parties would be established to
discuss points of contention.
Earlier, Mr Izetbegovic and Mr Tudjman discussed between themselves and with
the international mediators, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, the
vexed issue of access to the sea for the Moslem republic, a key obstacle to
a resumption of the Bosnian peace talks, which broke up two weeks ago.
Meanwhile, amid mounting pressure on the Moslems to return to the
negotiations, Lord Owen told a separate meeting of the 29-nation steering
committee of the international conference on the former Yugoslavia that Mr
Izetbegovic's demand for a port at Neum was 'second-best' to access to Ploce
on Croatia's Dalmatian coast, which the Croats have already offered.
Lord Owen added that, in the mediators' view, the Moslems could not expect
more than 30 per cent of Bosnian territory.
In another reflection of the attempts to recapture the momentum in the peace
process, Nato military planners are due to present to a Nato council meeting
in Brussels today documents for the deployment of Nato peacekeepers in
Bosnia.
In Croatia, UN officials were yesterday attempting to secure a ceasefire
after rebel Serb forces shot down a Croatian aircraft on a bombing raid. The
Croatian government confirmed a Mig-21 had been hit after conducting bombing
raids in Krajina.
</TEXT>
