<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (16): The cutting edge
 -Case Study / Bomford Turner / Paul Cheeseright charts a productivity drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN Bomford Turner's yard the stack of stillages is going higher and wider.
Pat's mountain, it is called: a pile of metal cages mounted on pallets. The
stillages used to ferry material and parts around the factory. Now they are
no longer wanted.
Pat's mountain, named after Mr Pat McLaughlin, the company's manufacturing
director, shows how the manufacturing system at this factory of grass- and
scrub-cutting equipment has been simplified and speeded up in the search for
higher productivity.
It is a common tale. UK engineering companies have since the 1980s recession
been in the throes of profound change and the process has speeded with the
recession of the 1990s.
Most of the changes in the manufacturing process at Bomford Turner occurred
last year, so the full effects are not yet apparent. What is clear is that
its plant, set appropriately enough for a company making grass-cutting
equipment near Evesham, Worcestershire, is very different from the plant of
1990.
That year, Mr Andrew Hall became managing director. 'The company had lived
off the past and like a lot of engineering companies it didn't really
develop,' he says.
In the trade, says Mr Hall, Bomford Turner had a decent reputation. It had a
parent - it is part of the Elswick group - ready to invest. But there was a
downside. The business lacked focus and it was operating in a declining
market.
Its main customers were in agriculture and the public sector, both subject
to financial pressure. Survival and future prosperity depended on winning a
larger share of a shrinking market. That forced the new management to
reorganise the business and expand the product range.
The product range had the first attention. It was decided to concentrate on
the UK, French and US markets. Customers were making it clear that they
wanted delivery at their convenience, not that of Bomford Turner which had
met orders out of stock or, if that was not possible, offered delivery times
of 10 weeks.
New products were out on the market, resulting in an immediate increase in
French sales and the return to profit of the group's plants in the US. New
flexibility towards customers became apparent. Like many other UK groups,
Bomford Turner was rediscovering the notion of service.
But flexibility to meet sudden and changing demands could not be obtained
from a manufacturing system which relied on making equipment in batches and
holding heavy stocks of work in progress. Nor, financially, could the
company tolerate the high level of stocks it was obliged to hold.
'The objective was to find a way to reduce the lead time from 10 weeks to
five days for volume products,' says Mr Hall. 'It was brought about not with
investment in new plant, but with detailed attention being paid to improving
the effectiveness of the existing resources of both plant and people,'
recalls Mr Paul Simon, a consultant on the project.
The chosen technique was not new. It was to establish manufacturing cells
concentrating on processes or products, each with a team of machine
operators. The effect was to shorten the chain of production, thus reducing
the material and parts held in the plant at any particular time.
Inventory has been halved by about Pounds 2m and sales per employee have
increased by 25 per cent. But, like other companies seeking higher
productivity, the payroll has been cut. In 2 1/2 years, the number employed
has fallen to 190 from 300. 'Most of the redundancies have come from the
overhead base. People who used to move materials around are not there
because the material is not there,' says Mr Hall.
The change in working methods was accompanied by changes in working
conditions, at least partly to reflect the uneven production flows: demand
for grass-cutting equipment is greatest when the grass is growing. Bomford
Turner introduced annual hours - that is employees are contracted to work a
given number of hours a year but on a flexible basis so that they receive a
constant weekly wage regardless of the hours worked in a particular week.
Overtime was suppressed. Terms and conditions of employment are uniform
throughout the company; only the method of payment varies.
For Mr Hall the past two years have shown that 'the major lesson in the
management of change is the handling of people - that is the key.' Deciding
where to place machines and the physical changes on the factory floor are
easy by comparison, simple textbook stuff.
Just as in the automotive and aerospace industries, Bomford Turner is now
urging change on its suppliers: if its own production is to be flexible,
then the production and deliveries of the suppliers have to be more closely
attuned. 'The suppliers are a harder nut to crack,' confesses Mr Hall.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Bomford Turner.
</CO>
<XX>
