<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (15): Taking the lead
in Europe - Britain's engineering institutions / John Dunn on the advantages
of selling to the profession in its international language
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN DUNN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FROM the outside, Britain's professional engineering institutions are not
the obvious places to seek advice on how to compete in the bright new dawn
of the single European market. Yet behind some of their fusty marble and
stone facades, there throbs a commercial instinct as thrusting and as sharp
as any multinational's.
The truth is that many of Britain's engineering institutions have been doing
good business in Europe for half a century or more. Some have sizeable
numbers of members - and sales - in almost every corner of the globe. For a
number of institutions, the advent of the single market has merely served to
hasten existing ambitions to take the lead in Europe - and the world - in
their discipline.
The Institution of Electrical Engineers is perhaps the most internationally
minded and commercially successful of all. Of its 132,000 members, 27,000
live overseas, with 3,000 in Europe. Worldwide sales of its books, journals,
proceedings and on-line database top Pounds 15m a year. Commercially, it
outsells its only real rival, the IEEE of America, which has over  1/4 m
members and with which it collaborates closely.
The institution organises the two-yearly International Broadcasting
Convention, which attracts up to 3,000 delegates, and is the publisher of
possibly the world's fastest reference journal, Electronic Letters.
In June the IEE opened a regional centre in the Czech capital of Prague and
announced plans for a further nine in the former eastern bloc over the
coming year. It already has 10 regional centres in western Europe. Next
month the IEE will inaugurate its first Chinese centre in Beijing.
Dr John Williams, its secretary, says that over the next five years the IEE
plans to play a leading role in the development of the electrical
engineering societies of Europe. 'The aim is to give the best possible
service throughout Europe and to be seen in Brussels as the first place to
turn to for advice.'
Electronic Letters is published every two weeks, and over 90 per cent of its
content consists of overseas contributions. Submitted papers are in print
within a record six weeks, says Dr Williams proudly. Later this year it goes
on-line - 'It will be our first electronic journal.'
Mr Gordon Rawlins, his deputy, believes the IEE 'has a duty' to take the
lead in Europe. 'We are much stronger than other electrical engineering
societies in Europe. Also, we have an international dimension that European
societies don't have. But the idea is to lead, not dominate.'
There are good reasons why Britain's engineering institutions should have
such a strong international following, says Mr Peter Thomas, who heads the
automotive division of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers. 'For a
start, English is the international language of science and engineering.
Also, there is a lot of admiration for our learned society role. People like
the fact that institutions such as the IMechE archive all their meetings and
publish proceedings. They can always get back issues or copies of papers.
Engineers are just like doctors and scientists - success is all about
getting your work published]'
The leading British institutions, such as the IEE, the IMechE and
Institution of Chemical Engineers are much larger and have much more active
memberships than their European counterparts. This stems from the unique
role that British engineering institutions have as qualifying bodies. It is
virtually obligatory to be a member of an institution in Britain in order to
qualify as a professional engineer. In the rest of Europe no such
restrictions apply.
Nevertheless, the role of institutions as qualifying bodies is much in
demand at the moment as former eastern bloc countries attempt to
re-establish their own national engineering courses. The IEE, for instance,
has been asked by the Hungarian government to set up a national electrical
engineering accreditation scheme. In the early 1950s, the IChemE, helped
along by Unilever and Anglo-Dutch Shell, provided a qualifying route for
Dutch chemical engineers who took the IChemE exams.
As a result, says Dr Trevor Evans, the secretary, the IChemE has a European
branch in the Netherlands. It also accredits chemical engineering courses
for the universities of Amsterdam and Keszprem in Hungary and Nancy,
Toulouse and Compiegne in France. Those who pass are eligible for membership
of the IChemE.
At the moment, says Dr Williams, it is an open question whether the
institution will expand into Europe by developing individual membership or
whether globalisation of the institution is the way forward. 'We have a very
high proportion of overseas membership - up to 35 per cent  - and we are
seeing a number of other UK institutions gaining significant growth overseas
as people prefer to join a single discipline society, especially since
English is the lingua franca of engineering.
'We will gather more and more membership in Europe, that is clear. But
eventually I believe that we will try to globalise through co-operation with
other European chemical engineering societies.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8611 Business Associations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
