<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (9): 'Keep at it' is
Parnaby's prescription - Profile of an industry guru / Paul Cheeseright
learns about competitiveness from a leading figure at Lucas Industries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHN PARNABY is a patient man. His job has demanded that. Now managing
director of the applied technology sector at Lucas Industries, he joined the
engineering group in 1983 with the brief of making its manufacturing systems
competitive. For that he has needed an eye for detail without losing the
shape of the big picture.
He has long believed that for British industry to be competitive, companies
require a new manufacturing strategy which opens the way towards flexible
production, the rapid introduction of new products and the maintenance of
exact quality. This is as much a matter of organising people as introducing
new technology, although the first may lead to the second.
He is accepted as an industry guru as well as a practical manager. He
embodies the drive towards the introduction of Japanese manufacturing
organisation in UK companies, not because it is Japanese particularly but
because it has worked.
In 1989, just as the first signs of recession appeared, Dr Parnaby thought
that Lucas, in its search for competitiveness, was about '40 per cent
there'. Now, he suggests, 'we are just more than 50 per cent there because
'there' has moved.'
This is not only because of the recession but also because customers are
making increasingly heavy demands, such as a 30 per cent cut in prices over
three years or a demand that component makers like Lucas shoulder more
front-end research spending. 'It all adds up to the fact that we've just got
to keep at it.'
It is the inability to keep at it, to apply the detail with regard to the
large picture, that Dr Parnaby believes is a weakness of British
manufacturing. Beating the competition can only be done systematically and
it can take a long time: 'the classical British approach is doing some of
the things some of the time but not all of the things all of the time.'
The length of the recession and pressure from customers have shown
manufacturing companies that quick cuts here and there, an attack on
development spending or an embargo on capital spending do not ensure future
prosperity. Rather, they jeopardise it. 'You can't do a piecemeal job,'
warns Dr Parnaby. 'You've got to put in place structured programmes.'
He divides UK companies into three. 'There are some good companies which are
making good progress; there are others which don't understand the problem;
and there's a group in the middle which is having a go but hasn't quite got
its act together.'
This state of affairs leads him to conclude that is 'why we need an
industrial strategy', by which he does not mean the government telling
companies what to make, setting the price and so on but, rather, 'the
government should be looking for what elements of infrastructure they should
put in.' It should be 'helping people to find out what to do and getting
them to do it.'
He cites enviously the policies of Germany, Japan and Singapore and looks
admiringly at the networks of technological universities surrounded by
technical institutes where small companies can get work done cheaply.
The reference to the importance of universities and research institutes is
not surprising. Throughout his career, Dr Parnaby has moved between industry
and academia. Indeed, he became an apprentice before he became a student.
Over the years he has published a series of learned papers about
manufacturing organisation and taken a leading role in the technical bodies
of the engineering profession. Even now, he retains a visiting professorship
in manufacturing systems engineering at Birmingham University.
A key influence on his thinking was when he spent lengthy periods in Japan,
trying to arrange for manufacturing under licence of the textile machinery
made by the company he then worked for. He appreciated that the Japanese
success in creating and sustaining competitive manufacturing companies
springs from 'a systematic attention to detail - handling the strategy and
detail together.'
The problem for British managers is not finding out about the management and
organisational techniques but the application of them within a company. The
Lucas system, adds Dr Parnaby, has been strongly influenced by Toyota, the
Japanese carmaker, with whose production system he began to come to terms in
the 1970s.
Although, in general, he believes that Japanese companies collectively have
been the best in the world at systems manufacturing, judged in terms of
measurements like output per employee, he notes that the recession is
causing them problems.
The market in the high volume consumer products which are the speciality of
Japanese manufacturers seems to be saturated. Frequently these products
trade on low margins and it does not take a large fall in market demand for
problems to appear, says Dr Parnaby. 'But they are underpinned by the team
structure and a culture based on training,' and they will respond quickly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Lucas Industries.
</CO>
<XX>
