<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (8): Why there's magic
in hydraulics - Case Study / UCC International / Andrew Baxter looks at a
company that has made a profit every month since it was founded more than 30
years ago
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the most common criticisms of the UK engineering industry is that it
is good - sometimes exceptionally good - at developing new products but
rather less successful at commercially exploiting them.
Justified or not, it is a charge that hundreds of engineering companies are
trying to disprove - often in the face of obstacles such as financing
problems and the need to keep shareholders happy.
One company that does not have to worry about the City or the banks is UCC
International, based in Thetford. The company was started more than 30 years
ago by the ebullient Mr David Button, who is managing director and owns 92
per cent of the shares.
Starting from modest premises in south London, Mr Button has ploughed some
highly profitable furrows for UCC, building the company into a leading
supplier of filters, suction elements and other more or less mundane parts
used in hydraulics.
Ten years ago, though, UCC branched out into system or condition monitoring,
selling meters that measure fluid pressure and flow rate. Now, it has gone a
step further by moving into contamination monitoring  - a step that brings
unprecedented challenges and yet, if correctly handled, could transform the
company.
Mr Button and his team are trying to plug a gap in the market that will be
familiar to any user of hydraulics, in everything from construction
equipment and machine tools to aircraft.
According to UCC, more than 80 per cent of machine breakdowns are caused by
fluid power system failure, and 70 per cent of these are attributable to the
presence of dirt. Contamination in hydraulic oil can range from being time-
and money-consuming in an environment such as mining or construction to
catastrophic in aerospace or funfair rides.
Traditionally, contamination is tested by drawing off a sample and sending
it to a laboratory for analysis, but UCC has come up with a sophisticated
portable monitor that does the job on site in four minutes compared with a
few days for laboratory testing.
The implications for the variety of producers and end-users of hydraulic
equipment could be enormous. Oil filters are often replaced before they need
to be because the traditional testing is laborious. So an on-site test could
save users thousands of pounds. Regular contamination checks with the new
machine could also reduce downtime and lost production.
UCC, says Mr Button, has a two-year advantage over its rivals in portable
contamination monitoring, and now has to exploit its lead.
The company has a number of things going for it. Mr Button notes proudly
that UCC has made a profit every month since he founded the company.
First, unlike many UK engineering companies UCC has no hang-ups about
manufacturing. Product design is done in-house, but beyond that, says Mr
Button, 'we're an assembly operation.'
And UCC can break some of the accepted modern rules of manufacture. It has
increased its stock levels in the current recession to ensure it can offer a
faster response time to customers.
Secondly, technology is kept in its place. The CM20 is a clever product
which uses the light source to 'count' the contaminant particles as the oil
flows through a small window.
But the technology is never seen as an end in itself and always as a means
to an end - creating a product that fulfils customers' needs at the right
price.
As a private company, UCC is also able to plough money into new product
development at the rate that it sees fit - nearly 10 per cent of turnover
which is very high for an engineering company. The CM20 took six years to
develop and cost Pounds 1.1m, but UCC was able to stick with it, undeterred
by technical hitches in development.
Above all, perhaps, UCC has an enthusiasm and thirst for success that starts
with Mr Button and permeates through the company of 140 employees. 'Magic'
is Mr Button's favourite adjective and this is a company which has not
forgotten that engineering can be fun.
Recent developments at UCC give a clear clue as to why many UK companies
fail to make a commercial success of a new product. Before the CM20, which
cost Pounds 7,000, its most expensive product was Pounds 400 and its
cheapest is Pounds 3.
According to Mr Mark Batting, marketing director, UCC soon realised that it
would have to establish contact with far more senior people than before to
make a sale of this type. 'Typically, the managing director signs off for
it,' he said.
About 60 per cent of the distributors it used for its other products were
not suitable for handling CM20, says Mr Button.
But UCC has also had to spend heavily - in time and money - on educating the
market about its new product, establishing its own credibility in
contamination monitoring, and finding 'champions' for the product among
potential customers.
All this requires patience - a rare commodity in British manufacturing. The
CM20 was launched three years ago and some customers have taken almost that
long to reach a decision.
The market for CM20 could eventually run into thousands, but Mr Button is
not letting the success change his basic philosophies even if contamination
monitoring doubles the size of the company. UCC will stay debt-free, and
would enter into manufacturing and licensing deals if its Thetford plant was
unable to keep up with demand.
Mr Button is also determined not to sit on his laurels or become too
dependent on one product. UCC's bread-and-butter products are not being
neglected, and new versions of the CM20 are in the pipeline. Coming soon
will be new products testing water in oil and viscosity.
</TEXT>
