<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (6): The details that
let the British down - Interview / Professor Kumar Bhattacharyya / Warwick
Manufacturing's founder talks to Andrew Baxter about the UK's need to let
young people use their talents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be easy to get the impression from listening to Professor Kumar
Bhattacharyya that the British engineering industry is suffering from
terminal decline.
The professor, who founded the influential Warwick Manufacturing Group in
1980, pinpoints a number of ills besetting manufacturing industry: a weak
intellectual base, lack of attention to detail in product development, too
many decision makers, managers who can cut but do not know how to grow
companies  .. the list seems endless.
But Prof Bhattacharyya acknowledges the good points too - such as the
tremendous improvements made in reducing variable costs like wages, and the
ability to develop products with less resources than competitors.
Over the past 13 years Prof Bhattacharyya has turned Warwick into one of the
largest groups of its kind in Europe, charged with the role of working with
companies, mainly in engineering, to develop the people and technology to
increase competitiveness.
In the process he has become one of the most influential observers of the
manufacturing scene, and is highly regarded by the government. The group's
direct involvement in manufacturing industry both in Europe and in
south-east Asia gives the professor a first-hand view of manufacturing
trends and the ability to make comparisons.
Looking back over the past 15 years or so, Prof Bhattacharyya says enormous
improvements have been made in UK manufacturing's variable costs - wages,
energy costs and raw materials. The shakeout has been helped by the
Employment Act and the disappearance of government subsidies, which forced
big companies to improve their variable costs and had a consequential effect
on the whole supply chain.
'This created a lot of following wind, so we ought to be more competitive
than we are,' says the professor. There are a number of linked reasons why
this has not happened, he believes.
First, he says, manufacturing industry's fixed costs have not been reduced
compared with most competitor nations. 'It has only been in the last
recession and this one that people started tackling that, because they could
not reduce variable costs any further.'
By fixed costs, Prof Bhattacharyya is not referring to tangible assets like
buildings but to the decision-makers in management who are not adding value
to the company.
One of the problems, he says, is that managers are judged by their ability
to cut costs so that they can meet budgets, rather than on how they can grow
the business. Executives restructure a company but never stay long enough to
sustain growth.
'When you want to grow, you don't know how to do it, and that's where the
problem has been,' he says. 'Companies have only been getting high profits
through restructuring, they have not had the vision to both grow and
diversify.'
But the problem goes deeper than that, he says. In the all important area of
product development, there is a 'fuzziness' in decision-making, caused by an
over-bureaucratic, class-ridden command structure where there are either too
many decision-makers or people are scared of making a decision.
With some exceptions, Prof Bhattacharyya says, the intellectual base of
companies in the engineering sector is 'pretty weak'. This can lead to a
slap-happy decision-making process in technology or other areas.
The professor draws a comparison with the 'robustness' of the
decision-making process in German and Japanese companies. 'When a German
product comes out, it is technically robust because their decision-making
process is very rigorous. In the UK we have the technology, it's better than
most of our competitors. But our products are always late and come out with
problems.'
The professor believes this is because, while the UK is very good at the
conceptual side of product development, it is in the detail where conversion
to a real product takes place. 'We have great problems with details and
controlling them. This is not a question of a company's intellectual
horsepower, but one where you need teamwork.
'You get a technological edge from a combination of fuzzy things brought
together - no single technology gives you an edge. The Japanese are able to
bring these fuzzy things together quite easily. Their system is much more
disciplined because of the attention to detail.'
Prof Bhattacharyya says the education system as a whole should not be blamed
for this deficiency - the UK's education system is not inferior to that of
the Japanese, even if the German system has much more robustness in
technology.
But he does lament the disappearance of the old technical colleges. 'They
used to teach all about detail, so the products came out pretty robust.
That's gone, because everyone now wants to be a manager with a degree.'
However, he does not believe the UK should be training thousands more
engineers to solve these problems. The solution is for companies to exploit
good people better, a task that Warwick Manufacturing Group has seen as one
of its key roles - seeding companies with large numbers of talented young
people.
'You've got to give people their head, let them use their talents in a very
flexible way to contribute to the company,' he says. 'That is gaining ground
in a lot of companies, but in a lot of others they just don't know how to
utilise such people. You can't give them lousy jobs, they'll up and go.'
And hiring - and exploiting - good people is the key to reducing the fixed
cost base, because, as the professor puts it: 'One good chap can replace 10
chaps quite easily.'
Prof Bhattacharyya's advice to British engineering companies is that they
should exploit the advantages of their lower cost base as fully as possible
over the next three to five years, as one can never be sure how long an
advantage like low wage costs will last.
'Look at Mercedes, Volkswagen and Dasa (Deutsche Aerospace). Even now when
you go there you are amazed by their robustness. What they need to do is get
a little bit broader and say: 'That's a good product, how can we make it
cheaper than our competitors?'
'The only thing they have to improve is their cost base. That's relatively
easy - we did it.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Warwick Manufacturing Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8741 Management Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Bhatacharyya, K Professor Founder Warwick Manufacturing
    Group.
</PE>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
