<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (5): Catalysts in the
boardroom - Consultants / John Dunn, deputy editor of The Engineer, says
that companies are now restructuring their whole business processes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN DUNN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WHEN I started in consultancy, I was doing feasibility studies on flexible
manufacturing systems like shelling peas. Now I can't remember the last one
I did.'
'Manufacturing technology is not an issue any more. Most companies have now
got their factories about right. We've done all the easy things.'
ENGINEERING consultancy has changed. The old adage, that companies could
afford to use consultants in the good times and couldn't afford not to in
the bad times, died with the end of the Thatcher boom years in 1989. In a
recession, consultancy is a discretionary spend.
But industry's demand for engineering consultancy and the issues facing
clients have also changed markedly over the past four or five years.
Companies now have a much clearer strategic view of what they want to
achieve and are beginning to examine their whole business, not just their
production operations or shopfloor technology. Also, the catalyst for change
is now coming from within companies themselves - directly from the boardroom
 -not from some consultant's report.
As a result, the consultant's role has changed. In the 1980s consultants
would recommend and then implement change for their clients. Today,
consultants are facilitators, not front-seat drivers. They are being hired
to help companies manage change themselves, to hold their clients' hands, to
give them 'ownership' of the changes.
Mr Colin Leisk of Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton says engineering firms are 'a hell
of a lot wiser' about what they want from themselves and from consultants.
'They don't want 'how to' manuals and they don't want us to do the work for
them. They want training and help on how to do it themselves. More and more,
it is not us doing the work, but the client, with us providing the framework
and inspiration.'
Mr Tom Cuttill, partner in Coopers &amp; Lybrand responsible for its
manufacturing business, agrees. 'Engineering consultancy today is about the
transfer of skills and knowledge to the client. Our business has changed
significantly. Five years ago we would have been very pragmatic, very
analytical, making recommendations on how to reduce the cost base. The
business was very consultant driven.'
But today, says Mr Cuttill, clients call him in to help them understand more
about the way their whole business operates and to reduce non-value
activities. 'Technology is no longer an issue. Nor is labour reduction. All
the easy things have been done.'
Clients are also much better users of consultants, says Mr Tony Roberts,
head of manufacturing practice at PA Consulting. 'In the boom market of the
1980s almost everyone used a consultant and they got to know how to get the
best out of them. Now they want consultants to work with them, not simply to
recommend a solution. They know the solution, the problem is how to achieve
it.'
Mr James Bentley at KPMG Peat Marwick reckons the UK is the most
well-developed consultancy market in the world - and the most demanding.
'The profession itself has grown up. The typical consultancy has been at it
for some years and has built up a stable track record. As a result, clients
have a vast choice. They know who to ring up to get a competent job done.'
In some respects, he suggests, the UK may now be over-consulted.
The result of all this, argues Mr John Crampton of Ingersoll Engineers, is
that industry has become much more competent at the 'easy' jobs such as
investment planning - new factories, new machines, new technology. 'I can't
remember the last manufacturing investment programme I did for a client,'
says Mr Crampton. 'Most people have got their factories about right now.'
Thus life has become very challenging for consultancies as the issues facing
clients have become softer, more subtle and more complex.
The big issue at the moment is business process re-engineering. There is a
growing realisation that the way a company does its business - the
information flow through the company - has a very real effect on the success
of that business. And the more successful companies are now turning their
attention towards restructuring or 're-engineering' their whole business
processes. They realise that every product or service they produce is the
output of a process - a series of operations and functions. And in order to
improve a product, it is necessary to look at the complete process,
examining each step in detail and improving it.
'In the old days you would look at your factory vertically and sort it out
function by function - purchasing, design, manufacturing and so on,' says Mr
Bentley at Peat Marwick. 'But today, you have to take a much more horizontal
approach. And companies can find that very difficult to do since it crosses
so many key internal boundaries.'
Mr Mike Tremouth, marketing director for the Peter Chadwick consultancy,
says the aim is to simplify the process and make it more capable of
delivering the right products by reducing 'the opportunities for defect' -
the chances of something going wrong. Typically, he says, this means looking
at a company's whole value chain all the way from the supplier, through
design, manufacture and distribution, to customer service.
'If you can reduce the opportunities for defect and can compress the time
taken along the value chain, you get real benefits.' It is a similar concept
to simultaneous engineering or parallel engineering, he says, to get
suppliers hooked into your business. 'Ideally, you should manage them so
that they become part of your business,' Mr Tremouth argues.
But it is not just the clients who are beginning to re-examine the way they
do business. The consultancies are at it too. Mr Bentley at Peat Marwick
believes that in future consultancy will come down to a matter of
individuals and their relationship with clients. 'Clients will only buy the
people with a track record. The problem for us is how to retain our
experienced people. There aren't that many new, clever things we can keep
coming up with to keep them happy. So, yes, we call in outside people to
help us look at ourselves. The future for consultancy is all change.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8742 Management Consulting Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
