<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (4): Design tool that
too many ignore - Guest column / Ivor Owen, director-general of the Design
Council, says the industry must realise that the key to survival is to make
more high value added products that the world wishes to buy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE has been a substantial improvement in cost competitiveness of
manufactured goods since sterling left the ERM last September. Yet the trade
deficit in engineering products is likely to widen during 1993, the
Engineering Employers Federation has forecast.
This shows that simply reducing product prices will not do much to reduce
the deficit or to protect jobs. To do this, more companies must learn that
the key to their own survival and to the health of the economy is to make
innovative, high added value products that the world aspires to buy.
Design is the key to this. It is the design process that controls the
transfer of technology to the final product. It determines the quality,
cost, manufacturing resources and time to market.
Design has a vital role in establishing the commercial success of a product,
yet the actual monetary expenditure involved in the design process is small
in comparison to the overall project cost.
In practice, the costs incurred are mainly those of brain power and labour
in preparing designs and developing prototypes. These costs amount to no
more than 20 per cent of the total. But it is at the design stage that over
80 per cent of the eventual product costs are determined. Companies have to
get the design right first time to avoid those costly reworkings which erode
added value.
The Design Council has recently carried out a survey of the engineering
sector, in conjunction with the manufacturing consultancy, EDS-Scicon, using
700 senior readers of the Council's publication, Engineering magazine.
This benchmarking survey revealed that 50 per cent of all products were late
to market and that this was fairly consistent across all sectors. The
average lateness to market was 27 per cent.
As a result, engineering companies are continuously losing substantial
profit potential.
The survey found that more than two-thirds of these companies overran the
development budgets of more than half of their products. The average overrun
was 19 per cent.
While this is nothing to rejoice about, the impact of this cost overrun is
far less serious than failing to introduce the product on time.
Concurrent or simultaneous engineering (CE) is now widely recognised as a
method by which companies can improve their performance, particularly in
terms of cost and time to market.
In truth, there is nothing new in CE. Fifty years ago, progressive
managements recognised the need for cross-functional communication and
simultaneous tasking between design, development, production and marketing
departments to reduce overall product development time and to design
products which more closely matched customer requirements. In essence, this
is what CE is about.
However, evidence suggests that British industry falls short in its
understanding of CE as a design management tool and how attention to design
and management of the design process determine a company's competitive and
commercial position.
The Design Council survey found that only 16 per cent of engineering
companies claim to have adopted CE as the normal way of conducting product
development, while 34 per cent had little or no understanding of CE.
Companies that do use CE report shorter development times, lower costs and
improved quality.
The take-up of CE is worst in small manufacturing enterprises (SMEs). Of
those companies with turnovers of under Pounds 50m less than 10 per cent
practise CE, countering the popular view that smaller firms are more
flexible and innovative in their approach to new product development.
This situation reflects upon the relatively poor value added performance of
UK SMEs. In the UK, only about a quarter of the total added value of
manufacturing is produced by companies with fewer than 500 employees,
compared with 35 per cent in West Germany, 41 per cent in France and 57 per
cent in Italy.
These shortfalls in performance are inflicting substantial losses on their
balance sheets. Yet getting the design process right is entirely within the
control of a company's management, unlike external national and
international factors, which are not.
One of the major impediments to the wider adoption of concurrent engineering
is the cultural shift that it demands. People who have not worked together
previously now have to do so on a day-to-day basis. They have to understand
the functions of other people and how they affect company performance.
The survey found that one oft-cited reason for not implementing CE within a
company was difficulty in getting people from different areas to work
together as a team. As the global marketplace becomes more competitive, the
key to survival will be to integrate internal functions, together with
suppliers, into a concurrent engineering operation.
Successful implementation of the CE approach to product development docs not
come easily. Managements must be prepared to persist, learn from their own
mistakes and take a long-term view. The survey found that senior executive's
pre-occupation with short-term 'fire-fighting' issues was the single most
important factor hindering the effective implementation of CE.
One UK defence equipment supplier initiated a pilot CE project about two
years ago. After only six months, the team was disbanded because of the need
to put more effort into winning immediate business with the current ageing
products.
At the time the team was disbanded, it had already identified Pounds 450,000
of annual savings through introducing better design for manufacture. At the
same time, the team was in the process of laying down the foundations for a
new and superior product which would have taken advantage of the latest
electronics. The know-how, the revitalised product, the investment in
competitiveness, were all lost.
But it is not all bad news. An example of good practice is one of the
winners of this year's Design Council British Design Awards, a microwave
test set designed and manufactured by Marconi Instruments in the UK.
Traditionally, up to four different instruments have been required to make
measurements and determine a fault on microwave and radar systems: a scalar
analyser, sweep generator, power meter and frequency counter.
The challenge facing Marconi was to combine the functions of all four into a
single compact device. Developments in broadband microwave technology made
this possible and enabled a reduction in both the number and complexity of
components. Combining the test functions of four instruments into one was
not the only challenge facing the design team: the man-machine interface and
control software for the transputer also had to be redesigned.
Using concurrent engineering techniques, the software and hardware were
developed side by side. From product specification to trial batch, the
development process took only half the time expected with such a
sophisticated piece of microwave hardware.
Although the approach required a substantial managerial input, nevertheless
it enabled faults and problems to be identified and corrected early on in
the development process.
Advances such as this will not produce long-term benefits unless they are
repeated on every new product development exercise. Generally, however,
continued attention to issues of short-term survival has left UK companies
vulnerable in the longer term. Discussions suggest that the product
development areas of many companies have been cut to the bone in order to
respond primarily to current market pressures.
When the market picks up, they will not have the capacity to compete.
While south-east Asian companies have invested in understanding how to
leverage competitive advantage from product development, some UK companies
have viewed this as a distraction from their main business.
So successful have many Japanese companies become in reducing the time to
market of their products that domestic consumers are starting to complain;
they are being overloaded with too many choices and products now have so
many functions that they are too complicated to operate.
What a nice problem to have to face] Taking these factors together indicates
that, unless the UK improves its performance, many products will not break
even during their projected life cycle. And this, it must be remembered, has
little or nothing whatever to do with the external economy; it is under the
control of the company's management team.
The engineering sector must recognise that the development of products which
are commercially viable and economic to manufacture is dependent on using
the design process to determine the collective issues of price, product
quality, customer appeal and service. Experience shows that the more that
companies practise this, the more added value they generate and the less
costly the process becomes.
</TEXT>
