<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Ingenuity - The FT Engineering Review (2): From profligacy
to investment - Foreword by the director-general of the Engineering
Employers' Federation / Neil Johnson argues there is not enough productive
capacity in the UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I AM delighted that the Financial Times is giving such a high profile to
engineering, the largest of the UK's manufacturing industries. By showing
readers the vital contribution that engineering makes to national
prosperity, what engineers actually do and what is happening in the industry
in other countries, the Financial Times is helping to correct the
anti-industrial bias which still exists in Britain. This survey is a bold
and imaginative step which will help to keep engineering firmly on the
national agenda.
Engineering is important. It employs 1.7m people, contributes some 8 per
cent of the nation's gross domestic product and provides 36 per cent of the
UK's total exports of all goods and services - an essential and
irreplaceable part of our international trade. Engineering products provide
the main technological basis for growth of productivity and living standards
throughout the economy.
However, we cannot take engineering for granted. If the UK is to remain an
advanced and prosperous nation, it must recognise fully the vital importance
of its engineering industry - as do the world's most successful economies in
Europe, America and Asia.
That means building a bigger industry for there is simply not enough
productive capacity in UK engineering. We have expectations for living
standards which the economy will be unable to deliver in the immediate
future. It will be unable to deliver them at all unless we rebuild our
industry.
Investment is the key to economic recovery. For over 20 years we have
gradually increased the proportion of national output we consume, increased
our borrowings from overseas and reduced the proportion we reinvest. Today,
we spend more than we earn and consume more than we can afford.
Our profligacy has caught up with us. To recover from recession, we must
have a massive increase in investment, reversing the trend of the last 20
years. There was a surge of investment in the late 1980s, but much of that
was misdirected into financial services and over-expansion of office and
retail property which was not actually needed.
Even including the property boom, net new investment as a proportion of
national output did not reach the levels that were normal in the 1960s and
early 1970s.
Almost all investment goods are provided by just two sectors of the economy
 -the engineering manufacturing sector and the construction sector. But
neither they nor other sectors of the economy are encouraged to undertake
long-term investment.
The government is now showing signs of recognising the importance of
engineering and manufacturing, but the acid test will be the measures the
chancellor takes in his November budget. To secure rising living standards
in the later 1990s, we must rebalance our spending today. Putting more of
our national output into investment now will mean spending less of it on
consumption. That will mean at best slow growth of living standards and
could well mean a standstill for several years. That will be difficult for
politicians to accept, but it is a reality which cannot be avoided for much
longer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
