<PROFILE>_AN-DINC7AGBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930914
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 93 / Money Markets: France holds firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPECTATIONS of further cuts in French interest rates were slightly dampened
yesterday after the Bank of France decided not to reduce either of its main
interest rates in its weekly money market oper-ations, writes James Blitz.
The Bundesbank's 50 basis-point lowering of its discount rate last week had
been seen as a reason for the French authorities to ease policy yesterday.
So, too, had the franc's strong performance against the D-Mark on the
currency markets yesterday morning.
However, the intervention rate was left unchanged at 6.75 per cent and the
five to 10-day lending rate at 7.75 per cent.
Mr Adrian James, international economist at NatWest Markets in London, said
the French authorities may still be concerned by the very low level of
foreign exchange reserves shown up by the Bank of France's weekly report
last week.
The December French franc interest rate contract fell sharply on the news
that rates were unaltered. It closed at 93.89, some 11 basis points down
from its opening level.
The story in Belgium was different, following the Belgian authorities' cut
in their end-of-day interest rate from 12.25 per cent to 12 per cent. The
December Belgian franc contract jumped 30 basis points to finish at 93.05.
The Portuguese authorities also eased rates, reducing their emergency
lending rate from 12.375 per cent to 12.25 per cent.
In German money markets, conditions continued to be tight, partly because
the Bundesbank did not help to bring call money down by providing section 17
funds.
The cost of overnight lending continued to be high, hovering around the new
Lombard rate level of 7.25 per cent. This partly reflected the fact that
there has been heavy lending at the Lombard rate level in the last two
trading days, amounting to some DM6bn. Dealers expected the Bundesbank to
add liquidity in its weekly money market operations on Wednesday.
Conditions in the sterling market were fairly easy after most of the Pounds
1.55bn shortage forecast by the Bank of England was removed in the early
round. The overnight rate of lending fell as low as 4 per cent at around
lunchtime. Three-month money closed at 5 7/8 per cent with a spread of  1/16
percentage point. The December sterling contract ended at 94.35 from 94.38.
</TEXT>
